@NODE iNTRODUCTiON "iNTRODUCTiON OF CALLER-SPY V1.0"

Caller-Spy is a Last-Caller-Util for Ami-/X 2.x and 3.x.

Sounds boring, eh? ........ Right!


So, what about this:

Caller-Spy is THE Last-Caller-Util for Ami-/X with NON-BELIEVABLE FEATURES!

Hm, sounds better, doen`t it? ..... OK, let`s check if that`s true:


First, Caller-Spy is implemented as a DOOR! Yeah, right, as a Door, so

EVERY USER CAN START IT EVERYTIME HE WANTS !!

And that`s only one of the great @{"Features" LiNK FEATURES} of CALLER-SPY.

Another advantage is, that Caller-Spy does REAL-TIME-UPDATING! That means,

every time it is started, it scans the Callerslog and shows all actual

informations out of it, including the ones from THE USERS STILL ONLINE !

So, Caller-Spy is not only an Last-Callers-Util, furthermore it is also

kind of a WHO-DOOR!

Just think of that possibility: You are logged in a bbs, and you can watch

all the user-activities by calling several times Caller-Spy, all the infos

of the Online-Users are steadily updated, including KB-Up, KB-Dn, Paging, 

Sysop-Activities, and so on and so on!



Ok, enough with that self-glorifying, just @{"install" LiNK iNSTALLATiON} CALLER-SPY and have a

look for yourself - I bet, you`ll never de-install it, hehehe!!

@ENDNODE

@NODE FEATURES "FEATURES OF CALLER-SPY V1.0"


     JUST HAVE A LOOK AT THE UNBELIEVABLE FEATURES OF CALLER-SPY V1.0:
     =================================================================


  - written in "pure" `C`  (Hi to all ASM-Coders out there :^)

  - VERY STABLE, shows correct datas even if the BBS was down for a 
    longer time

  - gets updated even AT RE-LOGINS!

  - shows AVERAGE CPS-RATE every user had

  - optimized extra program for file-output only

  - shows a front-ansi on top, with RANDOM-SELECTION, no matter how big

  - SELECTABLE Ascii, Amiga-Ansi or IBM-Ansi - Output

  - implemented as a DOOR, so EVERY USER CAN START IT EVERYTIME HE LIKES

  - REAL-TIME-UPDATING: Data is updated every time when started

  - EVERY USER can set up his OWN OPTIONS AND LOOK, EVEN TURN C-SPY OFF

  - you can watch AS MANY LAST-USERS AS you like
      (ever watched the last 100 users ? :^) )


    AND NOW I GUESS I GAVE YOU ENOUGH REASONS TO @{"INSTALL" LiNK iNSTALLATiON} CALLER-SPY V1.0

@ENDNODE

@NODE iNSTALLATiON "iNSTALLATiON OF CALLER-SPY V1.0"

iNSTALLATiON TO @{"AMi EXPRESS V2.xx" LiNK AMiEXPRESSV2.xx}.

iNSTALLATiON TO @{"AMi EXPRESS V3.xx" LiNK AMiEXPRESSV3.xx}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AMiEXPRESSV2.xx "iNSTALLATiON TO AMi EXPRESS V2.xx"

TO iNSTALL THE DOOR LOAD UP THE CUSTOMCOMMANDS (/X V2.2x OR BELOW) OR
BBS.CMD (/X V2.3x) AND ADD THE FOLLOWiNG LiNE TO THE LiST.


          11 SPACES iN         
          |
--------------------------------------------------          
*cspy     XM10DOORS:CALLER-SPY/CALLER-SPY
--------------------------------------------------
||        ||| |           
||        ||| ` 'DOORS:CALLER-SPY/CALLER-SPY' iS THE LOCATiON OF
||        |||    THE FiLE.
||        |||
||        ||` 10 THE MiNiMUM ACCESS TO USE THiS DOOR. CHANGE iT TO WHAT
||        ||     YOU GUESS iS ACCEPTABLE FOR YOUR BOARD.
||        ||
||        |` 'M' FOR A MULTiNODE BBS ('S' FOR A SiNGLE NODE BBS).
||        |
||        ` 'X' FOR A XIM - DOOR.
||
|`COMMAND TO START THE DOOR.
|
`-RETARD OPTiON. TO MAKE SURE THEY ONLY USE 'cspy' & ONLY  'cspy'
  TO GET THE DOOR TO COME UP. iF NOT USED, THiNGS SUCH AS 'cspyder' AND
  'cspy%$§%$§&' WOULD STiLL BRiNG UP THE DOOR.


  USE THE LiNE BETWEEN THE LiNES ONLY. THE OTHER PARTS ARE JUST AN
  EXPLANATiON TO MAKE SURE YOU KNOW WHAT EACH PART iS DOiNG (SiNCE
  NOONE WOULD TELL ME BACK iN THE DAYS WHERE i DiDN'T KNOW WHAT WAS
  GOiNG ON!)  

  NOW COPY THE DiRECTORY 'CALLER-SPY' FROM THE LHA-ARCHiVE INTO THE DOORS:
  -DIR OF YOUR BBS.

  BE SURE TO COPY ALSO THE USERS-SUBDiRECTORY INSIDE THE CALLER-SPY-DIR!!
  iT`S iMPORTANT COZ THE USERS OWN SETTiNGS WILL BE STORED iNTO iT!


  AT LAST EDiT THE @{"CONFiGFiLE" LiNK CONFiGFiLES}. YOU`LL FiND iT iN 'DOORS:CALLER-SPY/',
  NAMED AS `ASGLOBAL.CFG`.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AMiEXPRESSV3.xx "iNSTALLATiON TO AMi EXPRESS V3.xx"


THE FiRST THiNG TO DO iS TO COPY THE FiLES FROM THE LHA-ARCHiVE TO YOUR BBS.
BE SURE TO CORRECTLY CREATE THE DIR `DOORS:CALLER-SPY/` AND(!) iT`S SUBDiR
`USERS/`.

THE ICON `CSPY.iNFO` HAS TO BE PLACED iNTO `BBS:COMMANDS/`.
JUST ADJUST THE TOOLTYPE `ACCESS=10` TO THE MiNiMUM-VALUE OF THE ACCESS-LEVEL
A USER MUST HAVE TO START THE DOOR!


FiNALLY EDiT THE @{"CONFiGFiLE" LiNK CONFiGFiLES}. YOU`LL FiND iT iN 'DOORS:CALLER-SPY/',
NAMED AS `ASGLOBAL.CFG`.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CONFiGFiLES "HOW TO EDiT THE CONFiGFiLE `ASGLOBAL.CFG`"

=====================[Example Config-file]===========================

NumUser 10
NumAnsis 7
FrontNo -1
Display 1
CheckNodes 0 1
AnsiFormat 1
RowColors 35 31 32 33 35 36 31 32 33 36
AmigaFile ram:bull1.txt.gr
AsciiFile ram:bull1.txt
IBMFile NO

==========================[  cut here again   ]======================

What does that mean?

NumUser 10  <--- Number of Users that are displayed! (here: last 10 users)
                 Just enter the number you like, but be sure, that the
                 callerslog is long enough! (give it a try and enter `100`,
                 cool, eh?)

NumAnsis 7  <--- Number of Ansis located in `fronts.txt`! In the Archive,
                 there are 7 ansis, so if you add or delete some, just
                 enter the correct number here!
                 It`s important, to enter the correct amount, coz the user`s
                 input on his configuration-screen is affected by that value

FrontNo -1  <--- Select Front-Ansi with number `FrontNo`. if you wanna see
                 ansi number 2 every time, just enter `2`.
                 Enter `0` for random-selection, that means, every time
                 Caller-Spy is started you`ll see another ansi.
                 Enter `-1` to disable the ansi, so no ansi is shown!

Display 1   <--- Display-Flag. `1` means: show last-users on screen,
                 `0` means: don`t show them! So you can turn on/off C-Spy
                 without having to remove the ~CC_CSPY everytime out of
                 your login-bulletin

CheckNodes 0 1 < Just enter here the Nodes you like to be watched! In this
                 case, only nodes 0 and 1 are looked for, no matter how 
                 many other nodes are installed. With this option, you`re
                 able to keep your local sysop-node hidden from the users!

AnsiFormat 1 <-- Set Type of Output: 0 means pure Ascii-Output, 1 means
                 Amiga-Ansi and 2 means IBM-Ansi-Output

RowColors 35 <-- these are the standard-ansi-colors for the 10 rows of the
                 last-users-output! Every user can change these to fit his
                 own needs, but these are the default-values every user is
                 prompted with till he configures them!

AmigaFile <----- Only necessary, if you wish an output into a bull-file!
                 Just specify here the filename and path of the bull-file,
                 and add the command-line `DOORS:Caller-Spy/C-SpyOff` to
                 your logoff-batch.
                 enter `NO` as filename to disable the file-output, or just
                 delete this line!
                 Behind `AmigaFile` just enter the filename for the Amiga-
                 Ansi-Output!!

AsciiFile <----- same as above, this one is for pure ascii-output

IBMFile   <----- same as above, this one is for IBM-Ansi-Output
                 as always, enter NO (or just delete the whole line) if u
                 don`t want to have one of the mentioned outputs!


                      ==============================
                       iMPORTANT THiNGS TO MENTiON:
                      ==============================

The @{"USER-CONFiGFiLES" LiNK USER-CONFiG} in the `Users/`-Subdirectory have the same entries apart
from the entries `NumAnsis` and `CheckNodes`, which CAN ONLY BE CHANGED IN
THE MAIN-CONFIG-FILE (`asglobal.cfg`)!

`AmigaFile`, `AsciiFile` and `IBMFile` are also ONLY usefull in `asglobal.cfg`.
Second, they are only usefull, if you add a line in your logoff-batch like:
DOORS:Caller-Spy/C-SpyOff
That one is the executable ONLY for file-output!!!

@ENDNODE       

@NODE USER-CONFiG "HOW TO EDIT THE USER-CONFiGFiLES"

CALLER-SPY can be started from the mainline with the `w` option:

EXAMPLE:	cspy w


with that option, the user-configuration-screen of Caller-Spy is shown,
with the following options:


		(1) Number of users to show:	10

		(2) Display Caller-Spy:		ON

		(3) Show Front-Ansi:	    RANDOM

		(4) Ansi-Format:	Amiga-Ansi

		(5) Create your OWN STYLE


with the first option, the user can change the number of users, that will
be displayed as the last users. Possible values range from 1 to 999 :^)

the second option turns Caller-Spy on or off! So if a user doesn`t want to
see the last-calles every time he logs into your system, he just sets the
value to `off` and he won`t notice the start of Caller-Spy anymore!
The only way back is to turn the option to `on` again!

with the next option, the user can select, which front-ansi he likes to be
shown on the top of the screen, random-selection brings up another ansi
every time Caller-Spy is started! He can even turn the ansi off, if he only
likes to see the `pure` information!

the fourth-option determines the Ansi-Look of Caller-Spy. The three possible
values are: Amiga-Ansi, IBM-Ansi and ASCII. So every user has the possibility
to get Caller-Spy looking best on his terminal-screen!

Finally, by pressing `5`, the user gets into the Color-Configuration-Screen!
Here, he can change every row-color the way he likes, so the look of
Caller-Spy never gets boring (hopefully!).


                      ==============================
                       iMPORTANT THiNGS TO MENTiON:
                      ==============================

[to be continued ...]

@ENDNODE       

@NODE WayOfWork "THAT`S THE WAY CALLER-SPY WORKS"

               CALLER-SPY does the following steps when started:
               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~


 - it searches for the global-config-file in the Dir `DOORS:CALLER-SPY/`
   and sets the configuration according to the values inside if found


 - next, it searches for the user-config-file of the current user in the
   `DOORS:CALLER-SPY/USERS/`-Dir


 - if found, the configuration is read in as the current configuration


 - if both config-files weren`t found, the standard values are used as
   current configuration
  
   they are:	NumUser 10	show the last 10 users
		NumAnsis 7	use 7 ansis, as in the standard-archive
		FrontNo 0	use random-selection of ansi
		Display 1	display the output


 - after that, Caller-Spy checks for the value of the DISPLAY-OPTION:
   if it`s 0, Caller-Spy is terminated without any output


 - otherwise, Caller-Spy checks, which nodes to look for, searches for the
   needed callerslogs and displays the found users in a time-sorted order.
   it scans through the WHOLE callerslog, not only the LAST CALLER, to be
   sure, that the data is really up-to-date!


@ENDNODE       

